@startuml Hierarchical Supervision Tree - Multi-Level Fault Domains

title Hierarchical Supervision Tree: Enterprise Service Architecture

participant Application as app
participant "Root Supervisor\n(ONE_FOR_ALL)" as root
participant "API Supervisor\n(ONE_FOR_ONE)" as apiSup
participant "Data Supervisor\n(ONE_FOR_ONE)" as dataSup
participant "Cache Supervisor\n(ONE_FOR_ONE)" as cacheSup
participant "API-1" as api1
participant "API-2" as api2
participant "DB-1" as db1
participant "DB-2" as db2
participant "Cache-1" as cache1
participant "Cache-2" as cache2

== Initialization ==

app -> root: Supervisor.create(ONE_FOR_ALL, maxRestarts=3, window=60s)

root -> apiSup: supervise("api-layer", apiState, apiHandler)
apiSup -> apiSup: Supervisor.create(ONE_FOR_ONE)

root -> dataSup: supervise("data-layer", dataState, dataHandler)
dataSup -> dataSup: Supervisor.create(ONE_FOR_ONE)

root -> cacheSup: supervise("cache-layer", cacheState, cacheHandler)
cacheSup -> cacheSup: Supervisor.create(ONE_FOR_ONE)

== Leaf Process Spawning ==

apiSup -> api1: supervise("api-1", initState, handler)
apiSup -> api2: supervise("api-2", initState, handler)

dataSup -> db1: supervise("db-1", dbState, dbHandler)
dataSup -> db2: supervise("db-2", dbState, dbHandler)

cacheSup -> cache1: supervise("cache-1", cacheState, cacheHandler)
cacheSup -> cache2: supervise("cache-2", cacheState, cacheHandler)

note right of root
  Hierarchy:
  Root (ONE_FOR_ALL)
   ├── API Supervisor (ONE_FOR_ONE)
   │    ├── API-1 worker
   │    └── API-2 worker
   ├── Data Supervisor (ONE_FOR_ONE)
   │    ├── DB-1 worker
   │    └── DB-2 worker
   └── Cache Supervisor (ONE_FOR_ONE)
        ├── Cache-1 worker
        └── Cache-2 worker
end note

== Normal Operation ==

api1 -> api1: serving requests
api2 -> api2: serving requests
db1 -> db1: serving queries
db2 -> db2: serving queries
cache1 -> cache1: serving cache hits
cache2 -> cache2: serving cache hits

== Scenario 1: Single Worker Crash ==

db1 -> db1: OutOfMemoryException

dataSup -> dataSup: onCrash callback (db1)
note right of dataSup
  ONE_FOR_ONE strategy:
  - db1 crashed
  - db2 unaffected (continues running)
  - API layer unaffected
  - Cache layer unaffected
  - Only db1 restarted
end note

dataSup -> db1: spawn (fresh db1)
db1 -> db1: new process, new state

note right of dataSup
  Query routing updated:
  - db2: handles traffic during restart
  - db1: comes back online
  - Seamless failover (ProcRef.swap())
end note

== Scenario 2: Supervisor Crash ==

dataSup -> dataSup: Supervisor crash (internal error)
note right of dataSup
  Root sees: Data Supervisor crashed
  Root strategy: ONE_FOR_ALL
  All supervisors + workers must restart
end note

root -> apiSup: stop (graceful shutdown)
apiSup -> api1: stop
apiSup -> api2: stop
root -> dataSup: stop
root -> cacheSup: stop
cacheSup -> cache1: stop
cacheSup -> cache2: stop

note right of root
  ONE_FOR_ALL effect:
  All layers restarted:
  - API Supervisor (fresh)
  - Data Supervisor (fresh)
  - Cache Supervisor (fresh)
  - All workers (fresh state)

  Atomic restart ensures:
  - Consistent initialization order
  - No stale cross-layer references
end note

root -> apiSup: spawn (fresh)
root -> dataSup: spawn (fresh)
root -> cacheSup: spawn (fresh)

apiSup -> api1: supervise
apiSup -> api2: supervise
dataSup -> db1: supervise
dataSup -> db2: supervise
cacheSup -> cache1: supervise
cacheSup -> cache2: supervise

note right of root
  All processes back online
  Fresh state shared across layers
end note

== Fault Isolation Benefits ==

note over root, cache2
  Level 1 Isolation (Leaf):
  - api1 crash → api2 continues
  - db1 crash → db2 continues
  - cache1 crash → cache2 continues

  Level 2 Isolation (Supervisor):
  - API Supervisor crash → Data/Cache unaffected
  - Data Supervisor crash → API/Cache unaffected
  - Cache Supervisor crash → API/Data unaffected

  Level 3 Coordination (Root):
  - Root crash (rare) → entire system restarts
  - ONE_FOR_ALL ensures atomic restart

  Result:
  - Granular recovery (low impact)
  - Bounded blast radius (fault domains)
  - Fast MTTR (mean time to recovery)
end note

== Scaling Pattern ==

note right of root
  This hierarchy scales to enterprise systems:
  Root Supervisor (ONE_FOR_ALL)
   ├── API Layer Supervisor
   │    ├── HTTP Server Supervisor
   │    ├── WebSocket Supervisor
   │    └── GraphQL Supervisor
   ├── Business Logic Layer
   │    ├── User Service Supervisor
   │    ├── Product Service Supervisor
   │    └── Order Service Supervisor
   ├── Data Layer
   │    ├── Primary DB Supervisor
   │    ├── Read Replica Supervisor
   │    └── Cache Supervisor
   └── Infrastructure Layer
        ├── Metrics Supervisor
        ├── Logging Supervisor
        └── Health Check Supervisor

  Each supervisor can have hundreds of workers
  Each worker is a virtual thread (lightweight)
end note
